  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering, which involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate, is widely recognized as a serious criminal offense. It undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates organized crime, and can have significant negative economic and social impacts.\n\nMost countries have enacted specific legislation to combat money laundering, often in alignment with international standards and recommendations. Notable frameworks include:\n\n1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: An intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and related threats. Many countries adopt FATF recommendations into their national laws.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**: The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (the Palermo Convention) and the United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC) both include provisions requiring signatory states to criminalize money laundering.\n\n3. **Regional Agreements**: Various regional bodies, such as the European Union, have also established anti-money laundering (AML) directives that member states must implement.\n\nIn the United States, for example, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act include provisions to combat money laundering. Similarly, the UK has the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002, and other countries have equivalent legislation.\n\nEnforcement of these laws typically involves financial institutions, regulatory bodies, and law enforcement agencies working together to detect, investigate, and prosecute money laundering activities. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nWhile there may be variations in the specific implementation and enforcement of anti-money laundering laws across different jurisdictions, the fundamental principle that money laundering is illegal is widely accepted and upheld globally.",
